[
    {
        "content": "<p>I am looking for a name for the following generalization of the concept of isomtery in a dagger category:<br>\nIn a <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/dagger%20category\">[[dagger category]]</a>, an isomtery is a morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\rightarrow B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> is called an isometry if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>f</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">†</mo></msup><mo>∘</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi><msub><mi>d</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f^{\\dagger}\\circ f = id_A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0435em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">†</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8444em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">A</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and a partial isometry when <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>f</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">†</mo></msup><mo>∘</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f^{\\dagger}\\circ f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0435em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">†</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> is dagger idempotent. <br>\nIs there a name for a morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> with the property that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>f</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">†</mo></msup><mo>∘</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f^{\\dagger}\\circ f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0435em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">†</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span>  is an isomorphism?</p>",
        "id": 516864446,
        "sender_full_name": "Sascha Haupt",
        "timestamp": 1746701101
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Just some comments as to “why maybe there isn't a name already”:<br>\ntypically in dagger-categories it is “wrong” to talk about isomorphisms which are not unitary isomorphisms, so the more likely concept is: <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>f</mi><mo>†</mo></msup><mo>∘</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f^\\dagger \\circ f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0435em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">†</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> is unitary.<br>\nNow, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>f</mi><mo>†</mo></msup><mo>∘</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f^\\dagger \\circ f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0435em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">†</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> is also self-adjoint, so in particular being unitary would mean it is an involution.<br>\nBoth in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">l</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Rel}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Rel</span></span></span></span></span> and in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Hilb}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Hilb</span></span></span></span></span> there are no examples in which <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> is not already an isometry:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">l</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Rel}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Rel</span></span></span></span></span> because for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>R</mi><mo>†</mo></msup><mo>∘</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R^\\dagger \\circ R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">†</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> to be invertible, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> would need to be total, in which case <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>R</mi><mo>†</mo></msup><mo>∘</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R^\\dagger \\circ R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">†</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> always contains the identity relation, and so in order to be an involution, it <em>has to be</em> the identity relation;</li>\n<li>in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Hilb}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Hilb</span></span></span></span></span> because <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>A</mi><mo>†</mo></msup><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A^\\dagger A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">†</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is positive, so its spectrum is positive, but an involution must have spectrum in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{+1, -1\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">+</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span>, so a positive involution has spectrum <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{+1\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">+</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> and then it is the identity</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 516871682,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1746703553
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Now I think pretty much any “named concept” in dagger category theory is an extrapolation from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">l</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Rel}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Rel</span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Hilb}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Hilb</span></span></span></span></span>, so if there are no examples in these two I see it as unlikely that it would have shown up!</p>",
        "id": 516872132,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1746703700
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But there seems to be no strong reason for this to happen in general... Do you have an example in mind?</p>",
        "id": 516872232,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1746703747
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It is called a \"closed monomorphism\" by Matt Di Meglio in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.02883\">R*-categories</a>, because in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Hilb}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Hilb</span></span></span></span></span> it corresponds to a monomorphism whose image is closed. It's also equivalent to being monic and pseudoinvertible (a fact that appears in the extended version of my paper about pseudoinverses now available <a href=\"https://www.mathstat.dal.ca/~selinger/papers/mp-trace-long.pdf\">here</a>).</p>",
        "id": 516929490,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron David Fairbanks",
        "timestamp": 1746719625
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276363\">@Amar Hadzihasanovic</span> and  <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"546041\">@Aaron David Fairbanks</span> for your remarks, those are helpful to me. </p>\n<p>I am thinking about different daggers in the category of affine relations (where the morphosis are affine subspaces of some vector space). I don't have a concrete example for a closed morphism in that context yet.</p>",
        "id": 516963663,
        "sender_full_name": "Sascha Haupt",
        "timestamp": 1746731371
    }
]